3
00:00:09,019 --> 00:00:12,679
Their trade wasn't just about tears. It was about identity.

4
00:00:13,240 --> 00:00:15,199
They tore their clothes. They wailed.

5
00:00:15,460 --> 00:00:19,839
They performed despair so convincingly that over time, something strange happened.

6
00:00:20,460 --> 00:00:22,839
They couldn't feel joy anymore.

7
00:00:23,800 --> 00:00:28,640
Not because they were broken, but because they had invested too much in being broken.

8
00:00:29,579 --> 00:00:31,539
This is the sunk cost of personality.

9
00:00:32,240 --> 00:00:38,179
You know the sunk cost fallacy the way we double down on a bad bet because we've already poured money into it.

10
00:00:38,740 --> 00:00:44,420
A stock that's tanking, we hold. A failing project, we throw more resources at it.

11
00:00:44,700 --> 00:00:46,539
The mind does this with itself, too.

12
00:00:47,020 --> 00:00:51,880
If you've spent a decade being the cynical one, the lonely one, the unlucky one,

13
00:00:52,240 --> 00:00:54,079
you've built a kind of dividend.

14
00:00:54,759 --> 00:00:56,799
Not in money, but in consistency.

15
00:00:56,799 --> 00:01:01,460
Consistency. And consistency, as it turns out, is a cruel kind of currency.

16
00:01:02,560 --> 00:01:05,340
Most people chase self-discovery like it's a treasure map.

17
00:01:05,900 --> 00:01:08,099
For the maven, though, this is a dangerous game.

18
00:01:08,359 --> 00:01:12,620
Because if you find yourself, and you happen to be happy, you've just lost your investment.

19
00:01:13,040 --> 00:01:15,719
The dividend of being the person everyone expects you to be,

20
00:01:16,079 --> 00:01:18,840
even if that person is miserable, is strangely comforting.

21
00:01:19,519 --> 00:01:21,879
It's the difference between being a living, breathing human,

22
00:01:21,879 --> 00:01:23,980
and being a relic in your own museum.

